[2] Pennsylvania (Lehigh Valley)
Date: Wed 8 Jan 2020
Source: The Morning Call [abridged, edited]
https://www.mcall.com/news/local/east-penn/mc-nws-more-whooping-cough-east-penn-20200108-4jlkr4vvnvfxdby26embsxj63m-story.html


The number of whooping cough cases since 15 Nov [2019] in the East Penn School District has climbed to 17, with a new case this week at Emmaus High School. The majority of cases, 12, were in high school students, according to the district. There have also been 2 cases at Lower Macungie Middle School, one at Macungie Elementary, and 2 at Shoemaker Elementary.

Whooping cough, or pertussis, is a very contagious disease of the lungs and airways. Pertussis can be treated with antibiotics and prevented with vaccines. The state requires school children or school staff suspected of having whooping cough or have a confirmed case to be excluded from school or daycare for 3 weeks from the start of their symptoms, or for 5 days after starting antibiotics.

In a Tuesday [7 Jan 2020] letter posted on the high school's website, the district referred parents to state Health Department guidelines that recommend they contact a doctor if their child coughs frequently or experiences fits. "The best way we currently have to protect against the spread of pertussis is by being fully immunized," the letter states.

Pertussis vaccines are effective but not perfect, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Lehigh County has the highest rates of pertussis in the state, according to the Health Department: 30.5 pertussis cases per 100 000 people, according to 2015-2017 data posted on the department's website. Northampton County had a rate of 11.5 cases per 100 000 people. A Health Department spokeswoman said no other pertussis outbreaks have been reported in Lehigh and Northampton counties this year [2020].

[byline: Michelle Merlin]

