[4] Northwest Territories (Yellowknife and Tlicho communities)
Date: Wed 15 Jan 2020
Source: CBC [edited]
https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/yellowknife-tlicho-region-whooping-cough-1.5428641


The chief public health officer of the Northwest Territories has declared a whooping cough outbreak in Yellowknife and in Tlicho communities. There are 20 lab-confirmed cases of whooping cough in those regions as of Wednesday [15 Jan 2020], according to a news release sent Wednesday afternoon.

Last month [December 2019], the Health Department announced 8 confirmed cases of whooping cough in the Tlicho region. Those cases were "isolated and treated," the department said at the time.

Whooping cough is preventable with a vaccine, according to the department. Residents can get the free vaccine from their healthcare provider. Immunity may fade over time, so booster shots are offered every 10 years. Pregnant women should get an immunization between 27 and 28 weeks of pregnancy, regardless of when they last had a booster shot, says the advisory notice. The Health Department said people who suspect they have whooping cough should notify their healthcare provider and stay at home.

In 2015, there were 21 confirmed cases of whooping cough in the Northwest Territories, including in the Tlicho region, Hay River, Yellowknife, and the Beaufort Delta region. At the time, the office of the chief public health officer said the majority of those cases were linked to travel outside the NWT.

